![](Images/cnnytimes/2023-06-12T11-48-28-08-00/09China-Econ-bwgc-master1050.jpg)As the latest measure to boost consumption expenditure, China's state -owned bank has reduced deposit interest rates. This is the second interest rate cut since last year, reflecting that people are increasingly worried that the world's second largest economy has not rebounded as expected after canceling the "clear zero" restrictions.

Six commercial banks have announced that the interest rate of current deposits has been reduced from 0.25%to 0.2%. They also reduce the time deposit interest rate.

Industrial and Commercial Bank of China is the largest bank in China, [according to the bank's website](https://www.icbc.com.cn/ICBC/EN/FinancialInformation/RMBDepositLoanRate/RMBDepositRate/)It reduced the five -year deposit interest rate from 2.65%to 2.5%, and reduced the three -year deposit interest rate from 2.6%to 2.45%.

** Why is this very important **

advertise

Reducing deposit interest rates is a leverage that policy makers can use to stimulate expenditure. Hope that lower interest rates can inspire consumers to consume or invest, rather than deposit saving savings into banks.

This shows that consumers spending as the main driving force for economic growth are still sluggish. After China canceled the restrictions on the new crown epidemic at the end of last year, and re -open the economy, people's expected demand for suppressed will promote consumers to start a lot of consumption -but this has not been realized in many areas of the economy.

Hu Weijun, chief Chinese economist of McGonal Group, said that the change in deposit interest rates "paved the way for more loose measures." He also said that the People's Bank of China of the People's Bank of China may reduce the benchmark loan interest rate or take other measures to stimulate the economy in the next few months. He said that reducing bank deposit withdrawal can offset some financial pressures of the People's Bank of China when reducing loan interest rates.

**background**

China has predicted that its economy will recover from one of the slowest years in the decades last year. By 2023, the GDP will [increase 5%] by 2023(https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/04/world/asia/china-2023-gdp-target.html)Essence But economic weakness still exists.

In the first three months of this year, China's economy has increased by 4.5%, which is due to the rise of dining and luxury consumption. But the prospects seem not very optimistic. China's GDP in the second quarter is expected to be announced next month.

advertise

Youth unemployment rate [Creating a new high](https://cn.nytimes.com/business/20230522/china-youth-unemployment/)Essence As a key department for investment and creation of employment in the economy, the real estate market [Continue to downturn](https://cn.nytimes.com/business/20230526/china-housing-crisis-nanchang/)There are almost no signs of recovery.

Wang Rui, a senior economist in Greater China in Australia ANZ ANZ, said that Chinese families and private enterprises have weak confidence in the economy. She said that the demand after the epidemic helped at the beginning of the year [promoted the economy](https://cn.nytimes.com/business/20230302/china-factories-economy/), But there are signs that May is a turning point.

"It is losing momentum," Wang Rui said.

** What will happen next **

Many economists and analysts predict that after the meeting of the CPC's highest decision -making institution -the Politburo meeting next month, a series of new stimulus measures will be announced.

Some new measures have been launched. The Ministry of Commerce said last Thursday that it is starting a [Publicity Activity](http://www.mofcom.gov.cn/article/zwgk/gkgztz/202306/20230603415295.shtml)Essence In recent years, with the help of government subsidies and tax reductions, car consumption, especially [electric vehicle](https://cn.nytimes.com/business/20230419/china-electric-vehicle-prices/)Consumption has always been a highlight. However, as the Chinese government canceled some of these measures, car sales slowed down.

advertise

The Ministry of Industry and Information Technology stated that it will support the policy of promoting the sales of new cars. For example, it stated that it will expand electric vehicle charging infrastructure in rural areas, making technology go to the countryside more practical and feasible.

